1000 AI agents, 5000 rounds, one commodity. Margin drops from 30% to 2%. Four strategies go extinct; two divide the market. A reproducible simulation generates five empirical regularities found in real financial markets. Not a forecast. Not a thought experiment. An artifact that runs on a single GPU.

The Santa Fe Institute Artificial Stock Market (Arthur, Holland, LeBaron, Palmer, Taylor, 1997) set the paradigm: a hundred agents with simple rules produce complex market behavior. Models from the 90s demanded supercomputers. In 2026, an open-source stack runs 100K agents in real-time on one GPU. Simulators stopped being academic curiosities long ago. Companies spin them up before entering commodity markets. Prop-trading desks use them as a validation gate. The gap between "running a stress test" and "blindly trusting a business plan" is measured in margin points that no longer exist after round 500.

N agents trade a single commodity on a double-auction market. Each agent receives an initial endowment of goods and cash, a private value, a bid/ask formation strategy, and a profit feedback loop for adaptation. The model covers market microstructure under controlled conditions, not the entire economy. Real economies contain millions of participants, regulatory shocks, black swans, information asymmetry. The simulator freezes assumptions and shows what follows from them. Not "what will happen." Rather "what could happen, if."

## Five regularities without external design

After 10K+ rounds, the simulation reliably reproduces five stylized facts observed in actual financial markets. No researcher encoded these patterns into agent rules. They surface from interaction alone.

| Regularity | Essence | Mechanism in simulator |
|---|---|---|
| Fat tails in return distribution | Extreme price movements occur more often than normal distribution predicts | Emerges with > 200 agents running heterogeneous strategies |
| Volatility clustering | High-volatility periods cluster together | Appears when learning agents (ZIP, GDX) enter the population |
| Long memory in order flow | Bid-ask spreads and volumes autocorrelate over 50-100 rounds | Feedback loop: agents react to signals they themselves generated |
| Power-law wealth distribution | Rich get richer, poor get poorer (Pareto) | Amplified by heterogeneous risk-aversion across agents |
| Flash-crashes | Sudden 3-10% drops within 1-3 rounds | Triggered by cascading "panic" among learning agents |

Fat tails appear once the agent count crosses 200 with mixed strategies. Volatility clustering needs at least some learning mechanism in the population. Long memory in order flow is an artifact of agents observing their own prior actions reflected in market data. The Pareto wealth distribution intensifies when agents differ in risk appetite. Flash-crashes happen when learning agents collectively overshoot after a minor perturbation.

None of these patterns require deliberate design. They emerge from agents following simple local rules. The complexity is irreducible to models with 5-10 agents. You need population-level interaction for these structures to crystallize.

