## Survival by round 5000

A series of runs: 1000 agents, equal split across five strategies, 5000 rounds. Starting conditions identical. No external shocks. Market dynamics determined entirely by agent interactions.

```
Round   0:    ZI=200  ZIP=200  GDX=200  Pure-Aggr=200  Conservative=200
Round 200:    ZI=80   ZIP=380  GDX=290  Pure-Aggr=20   Conservative=230
Round 500:    ZI=15   ZIP=420  GDX=350  Pure-Aggr=0    Conservative=215
Round 2000:   ZI=2    ZIP=480  GDX=420  Pure-Aggr=0    Conservative=98
Round 5000:   ZI=0    ZIP=520  GDX=410  Pure-Aggr=0    Conservative=70
```

Pure-aggressive strategies die within 30-50 rounds. Margin compresses faster than they can retrain. The logic is simple: aggressive undercutting destroys profit for everyone, including the aggressor. ZI (Zero Intelligence) dies second. No learning loop means no adaptation to shifting microstructure. Random orders bleed capital slowly, then all at once. Conservative strategies shrink but persist. Small predictable profit keeps them alive. ZIP+GDX capture 93% of the market by round 5000. Learning loops and internal market models dominate.

A detail that surprises first-time observers: tacit collusion without explicit coordination. In 5-7% of rounds, ZIP+GDX clusters synchronously widen spreads. The pattern reproduces what regulatory theory calls a "silent cartel." No message passing between agents. No shared protocol. Pure emergent coordination arising from profit feedback loops converging on similar optimal actions.

The survival hierarchy tracks real ecosystems. Adaptation beats aggression. Aggression beats randomness. Predictability beats nothing. The simulation compresses decades of market evolution into hours of compute.

## The price spiral to zero

Separate experiment. 200 agents sell an identical commodity. Initial margin: 30%. No product differentiation. No switching costs. Pure commodity competition.

Rounds 1-20: margin fluctuates between 25-32%. Stability zone. Agents test the market, spreads are wide, profits exist.

Rounds 20-50: aggressive agents lower their asks. Margin compresses to 15-20%. The first wave of price competition begins. Agents with higher cost bases feel pressure.

Rounds 50-150: compression spiral. Each round, someone drops the price by 1-2%. The rest must follow or lose volume. The spiral accelerates because every agent faces the same incentive structure: cut or die.

Rounds 150-300: margin hits 2-5%. Individual agents trade at zero or negative profit. They continue because exiting means guaranteed loss of sunk costs. The market enters a phase economists call "ruinous competition."

Rounds 300-500: mass bankruptcies. Agents with the lowest cost base survive. 30-50 remain from the original 200. The rest ran out of capital.

Rounds 500+: oligopoly. 5-10 agents control the market. Margin recovers to 15-25%. The survivors learned that competition destroys margins, so they maintain wider spreads through implicit coordination.

Price wars are not market failure. They are the normal state during commoditization. Attempts to "hold prices" through informal agreements lose to agents who defect. The prisoner's dilemma plays out in market microstructure. One exit: differentiation. Leave the commodity segment entirely.

More on this: [[sober-budget-strategic-resource]]

The spiral pattern repeats across runs with different random seeds. Initial margin, population size, and strategy distribution shift the timeline. The endpoint stays the same. Commodity markets compress margins to near-zero unless structure changes.

## Scaling properties

| Property | 1 agent | 100 agents | 1000 agents |
|---|---|---|---|
| Price behavior | Random walk | Weakly clustered | Realistic stylized facts |
| Wealth distribution | Uniform | Unimodal with tail | Power-law (Pareto) |
| Collusion | Impossible | Random, fleeting | Episodic, 5-7% of time |
| Adaptation speed | n/a | Slow (ZI dominates) | Fast (learning loop > noise) |
| Crash frequency | n/a | 1 per 500 rounds | 1 per 100-150 rounds |

One agent produces a random walk. No structure, no emergent behavior. The system is trivial.

At 100 agents, weak clustering appears. Wealth distribution develops a tail. Collusion happens randomly and briefly. ZI strategies still dominate because the learning population is too thin to generate meaningful feedback.

At 1000 agents, the full suite of stylized facts emerges. Power-law wealth distribution. Episodic collusion. Flash-crashes every 100-150 rounds. The simulation starts resembling real market data to a statistician running tests on anonymized time series.

Complex market properties arise from simple rules. Cascades, bubbles, collusions are features of population-level interaction, not bugs. Attempts to "improve" behavior through regulation (price caps, margin requirements, mandatory disclosures) do not eliminate underlying dynamics. They shift them. Price caps create black markets. Margin requirements slow crashes but steepen them when they occur. Disclosures reduce information asymmetry but also reduce the profit opportunity that incentivizes information gathering in the first place.

The scaling results carry practical weight. Anyone running simulations with fewer than 200 agents is wasting compute on results that don't generalize. Anyone claiming market predictions from a 10-agent model is selling snake oil.

## How to apply the simulator

- **Competitive intelligence through simulation.** Before entering a commodity segment, run 1000 simulated competitors with market-typical strategies. Observe realistic margins after 500 rounds. More accurate than any business plan. If the simulation shows margin compression to 2-5%, reconsider entry or plan for differentiation from day one.
- **Custom strategies through reinforcement learning.** Run your agent against 1000 simulated competitors. RL training (PPO, SAC) on profit feedback. A strategy optimized in simulation may fail in reality. The model is always an approximation. Use simulation for rough stress-testing and filtering failed ideas before committing capital.
- **Product idea testing on simulated buyers.** Model 1000 buyer-agents with different preferences and budgets. Observe product choice share, price elasticity, competitor responses. Useful for go/no-go decisions on feature development.

Tools: mesa (Python, agent-based modeling), agent-based-markets (GitHub), sfi-asm (Santa Fe Institute reference implementation). Managed solutions: GenAI-Economy-Lab (commercial platform), Anthropic Agent Simulator. Custom stack: Python + asyncio, agent = coroutine, market = shared state. 1000 agents run as 1000 coroutines on a single core. 100K agents require 16-32 cores.

See also: [[ai-agent-architecture-2026]]

The production agent stack (MCP, tool registry, cost control, observability) needs the same discipline. Architecture that handles 1000 parallel sessions with 5M total tool-calls per day can handle 10 production clients. The simulation validates the infrastructure as much as the strategy.

## What it actually means

1000+ agent simulators will become standard strategic planning tools by 2027-2028. The prediction is not about technological novelty. The tools already exist. The shift is organizational: companies that test strategies through agent-based simulation before entering commodity markets play with open eyes. Those that don't play blind.

The margin compression spiral is mathematically inevitable in commodity markets with rational agents. Simulation shows the timeline. Differentiation is the only structural exit. Everything else delays the spiral without stopping it.

Limitations remain real. The simulator does not reproduce regulatory shocks (sanctions, tax changes, tariffs). It does not model black swans (pandemics, wars, technological breakthroughs). It does not capture heterogeneous agents with different time horizons, information asymmetry, reputation effects, or social capital. A laboratory experiment, not a crystal ball. The simulation answers "what could happen under these assumptions." It cannot answer "what will happen."

The practical implication: run the simulator before committing capital to commodity markets. If the 500-round margin projection shows 2-5%, either differentiate or stay out. If the simulation shows viable margins at 1000 agents, stress-test with 10K. The cost of running a simulation is measured in GPU-hours. The cost of entering a commodity market blind is measured in millions.

### Why simulate 1000 agents when real economies have millions of participants?

Closed-loop simulation with 1000 agents isolates effects inseparable from noise in real economies: emergent behavior, collusion/competition regimes, margin dynamics under different strategies. Laboratory experiment for testing market microstructure hypotheses, not a model of the entire economy.

### Which agent strategies produce emergent behavior closest to real markets?

Minimum viable set: Zero Intelligence (random orders, baseline), Zero Intelligence Plus (adaptive market-making), GDX (learning agents with internal market model), fixed greed, varying risk-aversion profiles. ZIP+GDX reproduces the core empirical regularities.

### What is the main result of the 1000-agent simulator?

With enough agents and homogeneous strategies, the market collapses into a zero-profit equilibrium within 50-200 rounds. Episodic flash-crashes lasting 3-7 rounds appear. Long-term, only diversified strategies with risk management survive.

### Can you profit from a strategy trained in the simulator?

Conditionally. The simulator works for rough stress-testing and filtering failed ideas. Real markets contain elements absent from the model. Prop-trading firms use simulations as one validation stage, not the only one. Always: out-of-sample testing, paper trading, then real money at minimal position size.

### How many agents are needed to reproduce the regularities?

200-300 for basic stylized facts. 1000 for crash patterns and collusion. 10K+ for tail risks and cascade effects. More agents yield better statistical significance, but compute cost grows quadratically.

